<dl id="un7029ab"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un7" href="#un7029">UN7: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un7all.htm#un7029ab"> (V.A.2) 29(ab)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 0 Greeks &amp; Romans had not,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">As for <mark>0</mark>, it is a very recent addition; <mark>the Greeks and Romans had no such digit</mark>. If we had been embarking upon mathematical philosophy in earlier days, we should have had to start with something less abstract than the series of natural numbers, which we should reach as a stage on our backward journey. <small> Bertrand Russell, <a name="BRIM" href="/udra/udex.htm#BRIM"><cite title="source">Introduction to Mathematical Philosophy</cite></a> (1919), 3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
